solution.p:
(a) 
We us the formula for the mean free path

	\lambda = \frac{k_B}{\sqrt{2}\pi D^2}\frac{T}{p}, 

where N_A is the Avogadro number.  The given system has

	 \amp p = 1.013\times 10^5\ \text{Pa}
	 \amp T = 25+273 = 298\ \text{K}
	 \amp D = 1\times 10^{-10}\ \text{m}
	 \amp k_B = 1.38\times 10^{-23}\ \text{J/K}.

The mean free path equals 914\text{ nm}.

statement.p:
The probability of different free lengths between collisions is given by a probability function  \rho (r), similar to what was done for the Maxwell distribution of speed, except that  \rho (r) is a different function. While Maxwell distribution was Gaussian, free path distribution is exponential.

	\rho (r)= A\,e^{-r/\xi}

where A and \xi (read shee)  are constants. Constant \xi characterizes the average distance between the molecules.
